    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence assessment reveals a U.S. military posture characterized by sustained training, ISR, and air refueling operations across CONUS and select overseas locations, with no large-scale naval deployments explicitly tracked in the provided data. The presence of multiple KC-135/KC-46 tankers (B762, K35R) at high altitudes over California, Washington, and Germany indicates ongoing global air refueling operations, likely supporting deployment exercises or regional contingencies. Long-range ISR coverage is evident with platforms such as the E-3 Sentry (E135) over Brazil and the AN28 (48d825) conducting stationary loiters, suggesting monitoring of South Atlantic and regional airspace. Maritime patrol activity is noted with the TEX2 (likely a P-8 derivative) over Texas, indicating routine coastal surveillance. Notably, the only explicitly tracked naval vessel is Japan’s JS Kaga (DDH-184), participating in allied exercises (Resolute Dragon 26, Valiant Shield 2026) with F-35B integration, highlighting U.S. emphasis on allied integration and forward presence in the Western Pacific. The absence of U.S. Navy vessels in the data may reflect a shift toward distributed, smaller-scale operations or a gap in tracking coverage. Overall, the intelligence suggests a posture prioritizing training readiness, ISR capabilities, and allied coordination, with no immediate indicators of crisis deployments or large-scale combat operations. The MQ-25A Stingray’s entry into low-rate initial production further underscores the focus on unmanned systems integration for future naval operations.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
